Get Data

Geographical Data

default.crs = sf::st_crs(4326)
fairfax.roads <- roads("VA", "Fairfax city")
fairfax.city <- county_subdivisions("VA", "Fairfax city")

City Development Projects

city.dev <- read_sheet('https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1bvJCJSDmoayfMljJs9ajSb4PN4waE5MKDoz9vewyax0')
city.dev$Lat <- as.numeric(city.dev$Lat)
city.dev$Lon <- as.numeric(city.dev$Lon)
pts.city <- st_as_sf(city.dev, coords = c("Lon", "Lat"), crs=default.crs)

Crime Data

id.crime <- "1Hdhg5dvPsb28gvkroUU99AKPcGu8rVCp"
crime.full <- read.csv(sprintf("https://docs.google.com/uc?id=%s&export=download", id.crime))

CLEAN DATA

crime.full$date.report <- as.Date(crime.full$date.report)
crime.full$dow <- weekdays(crime.full$date.report)
crime.full$day <- day(crime.full$date.report)
crime.full$month <- substr(crime.full$date.report, 6, 7)
crime <- subset(crime.full, !is.na(crime.full$lat))

SUBSET CRIME TYPE

crime.list <- c("LARCENY:OTHER", "SIMPLE ASSAULT", "DRUNKENNESS", "DESTRUCTION/DAMAGE/VANDALISM OF PROPERTY", "DRIVING UNDER THE INFLUENCE")
crime <- crime %>% filter(crime.description %in% crime.list)
pts.crime <- st_as_sf(crime, coords = c("lon", "lat"), crs=default.crs)

FACILITY MEAN AND STANDARD DEVIATION

facility.mean <- as.numeric(mean(st_length(st_nearest_points(pts.city, pts.crime))))
facility.sd <- as.numeric(sd(st_length(st_nearest_points(pts.city, pts.crime))))
## [1] 2096.929

CREATE BUFFERS

facility.buffer <- st_buffer(pts.city, 100)

JOIN DATA TO BUFFERS

facility.activity <- st_join(pts.crime, left = FALSE, facility.buffer["Property"])

JOIN ORIGINAL TABLE TO NEW TABLE

facility.activity <- facility.activity %>% left_join(crime, by = 'ID')
facility.activity <- facility.activity[c(1:23,43)]
names(facility.activity) <- c("number", "date1", "time1", "type", "date2", "time2", "statute", "crime",

ANALYSIS

There are five types of crimes that are the most prevalent within 100m of the 37 city development projects in Fairfax City. Those five crime types include, drunkenness, simple assault, larceny:other, driving under the influence, and destruction/damage/vandalism of property. Drunkenness is the most prevalent crime type according to count being 1,201, while the least prevalent is destruction/damage/vandalism of property at a count of 558. Although driving under the influence is the 4th most prevalent crime type, it is present in more of the buffers than any other type.

In predicting what will happen for the remainder of 2023, each crime type will remain ahead of all others due to the gap in count, but their overall count will change. Drunkenness will remain the leading crime type but I predict that driving under the influence will become the second most prevalent due to it geographical scope. Larceny:other and simple assault will continue with their high counts similar to drunkenness. Finally, destruction/damage/vandalism of property will remain low as it is much lower in count when compared to the other crime types.

When analyzing the hot spots present of all five crime types, those are located in the downtown area, the north east region of Fairfax and the north western region right above downtown. The only activity is present in these three spots. Analyzing the hot spots by type of crime, there is variation. All five types have a hot spot in the downtown area. Driving under the influence is the only crime type to have a hot spot located in the north western region. All crime types also have a hot spot located in the north western region.

I predict that the city development projects located on and near Old Lee Highway and Main Street will experience the most activity across all crime types. The city development projects located on and near Fairfax Blvd and Arlington Blvd in the north east region of Fairfax will experience the second most activity across all crime types but less than the downtown region. I predict that the city development projects located on or near Fairfax Blvd in the north west region will experience the least amount of crime activity then compared to the other regions. I predict that they will have more driving under the influence reports than any other crime type.

The data I used for this project includes crime reports, therefore the time used to map this data represents the day and hour the report of the crime was made not when the actual crime occurred. That being said, overall reports are most likely to be made between midnight and 2 am. When analyzing by day of the week, reports are most likely to be made on Fridays, Saturdays, or Sundays. Between the hours of 3 am to 7 am there is very little reports being made. The rest of the hours and days follow a similar count of reports. Driving under the influence, drunkenness, and simple assault follow the exact same pattern as the overall analysis. Larceny and destruction/damage/vandalism of property have little to no variation across day or hour when it comes to when their reports are made.

I predict that the majority of these crime types will continue to be reported on Fridays, Saturdays, and Sundays as it is consistent across all crime types. As for hour of the day, most of the crime reports will continue to be made between midnight and 2 am. For those officers working 1900-0700, this is a time in the middle of their shift they are able to make reports during low call hours. I predict that their will be more reports made toward the end of the 0700-1900 shift due to the high call count present in the middle of the day.
